      "id": "0dd45290_3ce9dcc3",
      "file_path": "integration-test/src/test/groovy/org/onap/cps/integration/performance/base/CpsPerfTestBase.groovy",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 70,
      "message": "Yes, I think you're correct. Tests that use small amounts of memory always report same usage across runs:\n   \n    4.72\t4.72\t4.72\t4.72\t4.72\n   \nBut tests using large amounts of memory tend to fluctuate:\n\n    589.15\t381.56\t266.63\t232.72\t634.67\n\nObvious explanation is that GC is freeing memory during tests.\n\nSo right now I'm writing tests for the ResourceMeter class itself, and I'm looking at a different way of reporting memory used.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6742,
        "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
        "username": "danielhanrahan"
      },
      "updated": "2023-11-14 15:41:14.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "f2852bd1_1cdd227c",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "f9d60648_7c88628e",
      "file_path": "integration-test/src/test/groovy/org/onap/cps/integration/performance/base/CpsPerfTestBase.groovy",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 70,
      "message": "CPS-1967 attempts to address this. We are now incorrectly recording current memory usage instead of peak memory usage. So if GC runs during a test, the amount of memory may be hugely under-reported (possibly zero). It may be some time before we have an adequate solution - Micro-benchmarking with Garbage Collection is hard!",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6742,
        "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
        "username": "danielhanrahan"
      },
